# While Loops

While loops continue executing as long as a specified condition remains true. They're ideal when you don't know in advance how many iterations you'll need.

## Basic Syntax

```javascript
let count = 0;
while (count < 5) {
  console.log(count);
  count++;
}
```

## When to Use While Loops

- Reading data until end of file
- Waiting for user input
- Processing until a condition is met

# Nested Loops

Nested loops are loops inside other loops. They're essential for working with multi-dimensional data structures like matrices or grids.

## Example

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
  for (let j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
    console.log(`Position: ${i}, ${j}`);
  }
}
```

## Common Applications

- Processing 2D arrays/matrices
- Generating combinations
- Pattern printing

# Loop Control

Loop control statements let you alter the normal flow of loop execution. The two main control statements are `break` and `continue`.

## Break Statement

Exits the loop immediately:

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 10; i++) {
  if (i === 5) break;
  console.log(i);
}
```

## Continue Statement

Skips to the next iteration:

```javascript
for (let i = 0; i < 5; i++) {
  if (i === 2) continue;
  console.log(i);
}
```

# Infinite Loops

An infinite loop runs forever because its termination condition is never met. While usually unintentional bugs, they can be useful in certain situations like game loops or server processes.

## Common Causes

- Forgetting to update the loop variable
- Condition that can never become false
- Logic errors in loop conditions

## Intentional Infinite Loops

```javascript
while (true) {
  // Server listening for requests
  if (shouldExit) break;
}
```

# Function Basics

A function is a named block of code that performs a specific task. You define it once and can call it whenever you need that task performed.

## Defining a Function

```javascript
function greet(name) {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}
```

## Calling a Function

```javascript
const message = greet("Alice");
console.log(message); // Hello, Alice!
```

# Parameters & Arguments

Parameters are variables listed in a function's definition. Arguments are the actual values passed to the function when it's called.

## Parameters vs Arguments

```javascript
// name is a parameter
function greet(name) {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}

// "Alice" is an argument
greet("Alice");
```

## Default Parameters

```javascript
function greet(name = "World") {
  return `Hello, ${name}!`;
}
```

# Return Values

Functions can send data back to the code that called them using the `return` statement. This allows functions to produce results that can be used elsewhere.

## Basic Return

```javascript
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

const sum = add(3, 5); // sum is 8
```

## Multiple Return Points

```javascript
function getGrade(score) {
  if (score >= 90) return "A";
  if (score >= 80) return "B";
  return "C";
}
```

# Function Scope

Scope determines where variables are accessible in your code. Variables declared inside a function are local to that function and cannot be accessed outside.

## Local vs Global Scope

```javascript
let globalVar = "I'm global";

function example() {
  let localVar = "I'm local";
  console.log(globalVar); // Works
  console.log(localVar);  // Works
}

console.log(globalVar); // Works
console.log(localVar);  // Error!
```

# Higher-Order Functions

Higher-order functions are functions that take other functions as arguments or return functions. They're a powerful tool for writing flexible, reusable code.

## Functions as Arguments

```javascript
function doTwice(fn, value) {
  return fn(fn(value));
}

function double(x) {
  return x * 2;
}

doTwice(double, 5); // 20
```

## Common Examples

- `map()`, `filter()`, `reduce()`
- Event handlers
- Callbacks

# Arrow Functions

Arrow functions provide a concise syntax for writing functions. They also have different behavior regarding the `this` keyword.

## Syntax Comparison

```javascript
// Traditional function
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b;
}

// Arrow function
const add = (a, b) => a + b;
```

## Concise Body

```javascript
// Single expression - implicit return
const double = x => x * 2;

// Multiple statements - need explicit return
const process = x => {
  const result = x * 2;
  return result + 1;
};
```

# Function Composition

Function composition is combining simple functions to build more complex ones. The output of one function becomes the input of the next.

## Basic Composition

```javascript
const add5 = x => x + 5;
const multiply2 = x => x * 2;

// Manual composition
const result = multiply2(add5(10)); // 30

// Compose function
const compose = (f, g) => x => f(g(x));
const add5ThenDouble = compose(multiply2, add5);
add5ThenDouble(10); // 30
```

# Array Iteration

There are several ways to loop through array elements, each with its own advantages.

## For Loop

```javascript
const arr = [1, 2, 3];
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(arr[i]);
}
```

## For...of Loop

```javascript
for (const item of arr) {
  console.log(item);
}
```

## forEach Method

```javascript
arr.forEach(item => console.log(item));
```

# If Statements

The `if` statement executes code only when a condition is true. It's the most basic form of conditional logic.

## Basic Syntax

```javascript
if (condition) {
  // Code runs if condition is true
}
```

## Example

```javascript
const age = 18;

if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("You can vote!");
}
```

# Else Statements

The `else` clause provides an alternative path when the `if` condition is false.

## If-Else

```javascript
if (age >= 18) {
  console.log("Adult");
} else {
  console.log("Minor");
}
```

## Else-If Chain

```javascript
if (score >= 90) {
  console.log("A");
} else if (score >= 80) {
  console.log("B");
} else if (score >= 70) {
  console.log("C");
} else {
  console.log("F");
}
```

# Logical Operators

Logical operators combine multiple conditions into a single boolean expression.

## AND (&&)

Both conditions must be true:

```javascript
if (age >= 18 && hasLicense) {
  console.log("Can drive");
}
```

## OR (||)

At least one condition must be true:

```javascript
if (isStudent || isSenior) {
  console.log("Discount applies");
}
```

## NOT (!)

Inverts the boolean value:

```javascript
if (!isLoggedIn) {
  console.log("Please log in");
}
```

# Switch Statements

Switch statements provide a clean way to handle multiple possible values of a single variable.

## Basic Syntax

```javascript
switch (day) {
  case "Monday":
    console.log("Start of week");
    break;
  case "Friday":
    console.log("Almost weekend!");
    break;
  default:
    console.log("Regular day");
}
```

## When to Use Switch

- Multiple conditions checking the same variable
- Checking against specific values (not ranges)
- Cleaner than long if-else chains

# Conditional Logic

Conditional logic involves combining and structuring conditions to make complex decisions in your programs.

## Nested Conditions

```javascript
if (isLoggedIn) {
  if (isAdmin) {
    showAdminPanel();
  } else {
    showUserDashboard();
  }
}
```

## Guard Clauses

Return early to simplify logic:

```javascript
function processOrder(order) {
  if (!order) return "No order";
  if (!order.items.length) return "Empty order";

  // Main logic here
  return processItems(order.items);
}
```

# Classes

Classes are blueprints for creating objects with shared properties and methods. They're fundamental to object-oriented programming.

## Basic Class

```javascript
class Person {
  constructor(name, age) {
    this.name = name;
    this.age = age;
  }

  greet() {
    return `Hello, I'm ${this.name}`;
  }
}

const alice = new Person("Alice", 30);
console.log(alice.greet());
```

# Objects

Objects are collections of key-value pairs. They're used to group related data and functionality together.

## Creating Objects

```javascript
const person = {
  name: "Alice",
  age: 30,
  greet() {
    return `Hello, I'm ${this.name}`;
  }
};
```

## Accessing Properties

```javascript
console.log(person.name);       // Alice
console.log(person["age"]);     // 30
console.log(person.greet());    // Hello, I'm Alice
```
